On 15 March 1988, a narcotics agent and a policeman at Los Angeles
Airport were searching for the companion of a black drug courier
suspect.  When Clayton Searle, the policeman, saw a black man that he
thought would fit this description, he moved forward to question him.
The two men became embroiled in a fight and Searle handcuffed him.

Later, Searle realized that he had falsely arrested Joe Morgan,
retired star infielder of the Cincinnati Reds.

By 7 August, 1990, Morgan was preparing to sue Searle and the City of
Los Angeles for being targeted as a black and for police
profiling.</SUM>

<SUM
DOCSET="d06"
TYPE="PERDOC"
SIZE="100"
DOCREF="SJMN91-06191081"
SELECTOR="A"
SUMMARIZER="E">    

The beating of black motorist Rodney King by Los Angeles police
officers has brought the formation of a panel to investigate the
department.  The panel, specifically focusing on racism and brutality,
neither blames nor exonerates the department's chief, Daryl Gates.

The panel did uncover racially derogatory messages passed on computer
terminals of police cars.  Black police officers related their
experiences with racial harassment and the existence of double
departmental standards.

One organization said that black and Latino minorities view the Los
Angeles Police as a white, male-dominated organization that has
subjected them to years of brutality and ignored their
complaints.</SUM>

<SUM
DOCSET="d06"
TYPE="PERDOC"
SIZE="100"
DOCREF="WSJ910710-0148"
SELECTOR="A"
SUMMARIZER="E">    

A report by a commission headed by former Deputy Secretary of State
Warren Christopher on the Los Angeles Police Department was issued on
9 July, 1991.  The report, prompted by the videotaped beating of
Rodney King, describes a department riddled by brutality and racism.
It calls for the resignation of its chief, Daryl Gates.

Other highlights of the report include the following:

a. A chief should be limited to two 5-year terms.  b. Departmental
training promotes a siege mentality.  c. A code of silence exists in
regard to community complaints.  d. There is a pattern of acceptance
of officers who violate rules of excessive force.</SUM>

<SUM
DOCSET="d06"
TYPE="PERDOC"
SIZE="100"
DOCREF="FT922-10200"
SELECTOR="A"
SUMMARIZER="E">    

In the past, they said that Daryl Gates was the chief of one of the
most brutal and racist police forces in the nation.  In May 1992 he
stands accused of encouraging the violence of rioting and allowing his
police force to do nothing to stop it.  In short, his force was
overwhelmed.  During his tenure, his police force has become
aggressive and insensitive.  It is completely alienated from the
community.  A recent review panel recommended his removal and the
institution of foot patrols as well as the investigation of police
complaints.

Gates has agreed to step down in June 1992.</SUM>

<SUM
