SIZE="100"
DOCREF="LA030489-0068"
SELECTOR="A"
SUMMARIZER="E">    

On January 14, 1989 a white Long Beach policeman, Dickey, pushed a
black man, Jackson, through a plate glass window after a routine
traffic stop.  The incident was taped by a news team as part of a
sting operation arranged by Jackson, an undercover policeman.  The
objective was to prove charges of racism and brutality by the Long
Beach Police.

Several investigations have begun.  Dickey has discredited his own
report of the incident.

Dickey also hurt Jackson by bending his fingers and refused to loosen
handcuffs.

Jackson told a hearing that he is committed to upholding the law as an
anti-brutality specialist.</SUM>

<SUM
DOCSET="d06"
TYPE="PERDOC"
SIZE="100"
DOCREF="LA011889-0067"
SELECTOR="A"
SUMMARIZER="E">    

On January 18, 1989, the Los Angeles County district attorney's office
was investigating a videotaped account of a Long Beach white policeman
shoving a black man's head and arm through a glass window after a
traffic stop.  The incident happened on 14 January 1989.

The arrested black man was Sgt. Don Jackson of the Hawthorne police
force.  He and a companion, federal corrections officer Jeff Hull,
dressed in shabby clothes and in an old car, set up a sting operation
to prove the abuse of minorities by Long Beach police.  The sting
apparently worked well.  The incident was covered by a van with a
television news team.</SUM>

<SUM
DOCSET="d06"
TYPE="PERDOC"
SIZE="100"
DOCREF="AP890117-0132"
SELECTOR="A"
SUMMARIZER="E">    

A black police sergeant, Don Jackson, set up a sting operation against
the Long Beach police in early 1989.  Jackson arranged to have a news
team follow him and a companion in their car through a high crime area
of Long Beach.  The tape shows a white officer searching Jackson with
his hands up, then pushing him through a plate glass window.  The tape
is played before a national audience.
  
Long Beach officials promised an investigation.  Jackson's supervisor
said he was looking for trouble.  Jackson chose the Long Beach police
because of the large number of complaints by minorities.</SUM>

<SUM
