DOCREF="SJMN91-06129119"
SELECTOR="A"
SUMMARIZER="E">    

A practicing attorney in Santa Clara recently wrote an item for the
media in which he describes a case of police brutality against a
suspect involved in a high speed chase.

The suspect is caught and brutally mauled by police, although not
resisting arrest.  The brutality is covered up by the police but there
are four witnesses who state otherwise and describe the beating.  The
officer is later arrested and prosecuted.

The article's author mentions the problem of police secrecy in
discipline cases and emphasizes the need across the board for
citizen's review boards to track complaints about the police.</SUM>

<SUM
DOCSET="d06"
TYPE="PERDOC"
SIZE="100"
DOCREF="LA071590-0068"
SELECTOR="A"
SUMMARIZER="E">       

Since July, 1988, the Ventura County district attorney's office has
refused to prosecute a number of suspects arrested by police who
contend that they were victims of police brutality and filed charges.
The public defender's office believes that this is a rare occurrence.

Typical was the police response to complaints about a loud party.
Without provocation, police began beating three of the partygoers.
Police arrested one of the men on grounds of resisting arrest and
assaulting an officer.  Later, the latter charge was dropped.

A similar sequence occurred in several other cases.  Reasons for case
dismissals included "lack of evidence."</SUM>

<SUM
DOCSET="d06"
TYPE="PERDOC"
SIZE="100"
DOCREF="LA010890-0031"
SELECTOR="A"
SUMMARIZER="E">     

Los Angeles Police, in January 1990, were applying painful techniques
in getting non-violent, anti-abortion protesters to comply.  These
methods, twisting arms, etc., are called "pain compliance" techniques.

Traditional political viewpoints are reversed.  Pro-choice liberals
support the police while anti-abortion republicans voice "police
state" rhetoric.

Protesters complain that police "come along" holds result in serious
injuries and have filed complaints.

The volatility of the abortion issue clouds the way many think about
police use of force.

A police authority says restrictions on pain compliance techniques
will embolden demonstrators.  An opposing view is that using pain
techniques on non-violent demonstrators is barbaric.</SUM>

<SUM
DOCSET="d06"
TYPE="PERDOC"
SIZE="100"
DOCREF="SJMN91-06195131"
SELECTOR="A"
SUMMARIZER="E">     

Police forces in 50 cities in the U.S. have been charged with
brutality and excessive use of force against anti-abortion activists.
Some arrests have led to injury and sexual abuse of women
demonstrators.  Operation Rescue includes mostly Catholic and
Protestant participants.  They do not use force and have instructions
to go limp when being arrested.  They do not appear to have much
public support.

Operation Rescue demonstrators are involved in denying some citizens
their rights.  Perhaps this is the reason why there is some reluctance
on the part of civil rights authorities to pursue police brutality
cases involving Rescue demonstrators.</SUM>
